Crop Prediction dataset

In this notebook we will explore the "Crop prediction" dataset and we will use this data to create a ML model. The dataset has numerous observation from different fields in India. For each field we find:

  • N - ratio of Nitrogen content in soil;
  • P - ratio of Phosphorous content in soil;
  • K - ratio of Potassium content in soil;
  • temperature - temperature in degree Celsius;
  • humidity - relative humidity in %;
  • ph - ph value of the soil;
  • rainfall - rainfall in mm;
  • label - crop that is cultivate in the field.

We will first explore the data, then reply to some questions regarding the different crops and finally deply a ML model to predict from the characteristics of a field which is the best crop to cultivate there.

In[]:
df= pd.read_csv("Crop_recommendation.csv")

There are 22 different categories and the dataset is perfectly balanced, with 100 observations for each category.

Prediction of the optimal crop from the field characteristics

In order to predict the optimal crop from the field characteristics we use Random Forrest algorithm. In order to do so:

  1. we divide our dataset into training set and test set;
  2. we use k-fold cross validation and a grid search approach to optimize the parameters "n_estimators" and "max_depth";
  3. we take a look at the performances on the training set of the models trained with different parameters combinations;
  4. we train the model with the best parameters on the whole training set;
  5. we use the trainig model on unseen data (the test set) and evaluate its performances using accuracy, precision, f1-score and by visualizing the confusion matrix.
In[]:
features= df.drop(columns=['label'])

x_train, x_test, y_train, y_test= train_test_split(features, df['label'], stratify= df['label'])

rf= RandomForestClassifier()
parameters= {"n_estimators": [5, 50, 200], "max_depth": [2, 4, 8, 16, 32, None]}

cv= GridSearchCV(rf, parameters, cv=5, verbose=3)
In[]:
cv.fit(x_train, y_train)

cv_results= pd.DataFrame(cv.cv_results_)

Before commenting on the model performances, we check what are the most importan features in our model and visualize them.

In[]:
feature_names= list(df.columns)
feature_names.remove('label')

result= permutation_importance(rf, x_test, y_test, n_repeats=10, random_state=42)

forest_importances= pd.Series(result.importances_mean, index=feature_names)

fig, ax= plt.subplots()
forest_importances.plot.bar(yerr=result.importances_std, ax=ax)
ax.set_title("Feature importances using permutation on full model")
ax.set_ylabel("Mean accuracy decrease")
fig.tight_layout()
plt.show()

We notice from the feature importance plot that the most impoprtant feature is humidity, followed by rainfall and N. The least important features are temperature and ph.

The model performs in an good (maybe too good) way. The reason for this extremely good performance, other than the parameter optimization, can be found in the extreme quality of the dataset, that is perfectly balanced and shows a strong characterization for the various features, as one can notice from the clusters in the scatter matrix.

Nonetheless this notebook shows how to approach the exploration of a dataframe and the deployment of a Random forest algorithm.
